Mgcb Configuration:  
 ![](http://i.imgur.com/kEgRPPv.png)
- Version: MonoGame 3.5 for VisualStudio
- Previous Versions: None
- VisualStudio 2015 Community, Windows 10 Home x64
- Cross platform GL project type
- [FBX](http://puu.sh/o0unl/c28cdabf64.FBX)
- [XNB](http://puu.sh/o0uoB/526fd23767.xnb)
- [MGCB](http://puu.sh/o0up2/25e6dd812e.mgcb)
- Works with this [OBJ](http://puu.sh/o0uHV/75530c5018.obj)

I'm aware that the internals of Shader and the Effect classes are likely to change in the near future.  One thing I'd like to see is the ability for games (and in particular, engines written on top of MonoGame) to be able to initialize the Shader class and Effect class without requiring them to write out shaders in the MGFX format.

In particular, I want to be able to support geometry shaders before the file format is updated to support it (I really don't like touching the file format because when it gets changed everyone has to recompile their assets).

My proposal here is to replace the BinaryReader on Shader and Effect, with an interface like `IShaderReader` and `IEffectReader`.  `IShaderReader` would look like:

``` csharp
namespace Microsoft.Xna.Framework.Graphics
{
    public interface IShaderReader
    {
        ShaderStage GetStage();

        byte[] GetBytecode();

        int GetSamplerCount();

        SamplerType GetSamplerType(int samplerIndex);

        int GetSamplerTextureSlot(int samplerIndex);

        int GetSamplerSamplerSlot(int samplerIndex);

        SamplerState GetSamplerState(int samplerIndex);

        string GetSamplerName(int samplerIndex);

        int GetSamplerParameter(int samplerIndex);

        int GetConstantBufferCount();

        int GetConstantBufferValue(int constantBufferIndex);
    }
}
```

Internally MonoGame can use a BinaryReader-based version of this for MGFX files, while other engines can load shaders and effects through their own systems.  This also raises the possibility of having backwards compatibility in the MGFX format because you can swap out the implementation of the interface based on the version number in the MGFX file.
